# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dimensionality-reduction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] In machine learning, **feature selection** is the process of selecting a subset of relevant features (variables, predictors) for use in model construction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The central premise when using feature selection is that data sometimes contains features that are *redundant* or *irrelevant*, and can thus be removed without incurring much loss of information.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Redundancy and irrelevance are two distinct notions, since one relevant feature may be redundant in the presence of another relevant feature with which it is strongly correlated.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Feature extraction creates new features from functions of the original features, whereas feature selection finds a subset of the features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Feature selection techniques are often used in domains where there are many features and comparatively few samples (data points).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] A feature selection algorithm can be seen as the combination of a search technique for proposing new feature subsets, along with an evaluation measure which scores the different feature subsets.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The simplest algorithm is to test each possible subset of features finding the one which minimizes the error rate.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] This is an exhaustive search of the space, and is computationally intractable for all but the smallest of feature sets.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The choice of evaluation metric heavily influences the algorithm, and it is these evaluation metrics which distinguish between the three main categories of feature selection algorithms: wrappers, filters and embedded methods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] In traditional regression analysis, the most popular form of feature selection is stepwise regression, which is a wrapper technique.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] It is a greedy algorithm that adds the best feature (or deletes the worst feature) at each round.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The main control issue is deciding when to stop the algorithm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] In machine learning, this is typically done by cross-validation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] In statistics, some criteria are optimized.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] This leads to the inherent problem of nesting.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] More robust methods have been explored, such as branch and bound and piecewise linear network.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Subset selection evaluates a subset of features as a group for suitability.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Subset selection algorithms can be broken up into wrappers, filters, and embedded methods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Wrappers use a search algorithm to search through the space of possible features and evaluate each subset by running a model on the subset.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Wrappers can be computationally expensive and have a risk of over fitting to the model.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Filters are similar to wrappers in the search approach, but instead of evaluating against a model, a simpler filter is evaluated.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Embedded techniques are embedded in, and specific to, a model.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Many popular search approaches use greedy hill climbing, which iteratively evaluates a candidate subset of features, then modifies the subset and evaluates if the new subset is an improvement over the old.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Evaluation of the subsets requires a scoring metric that grades a subset of features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Exhaustive search is generally impractical, so at some implementor (or operator) defined stopping point, the subset of features with the highest score discovered up to that point is selected as the satisfactory feature subset.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The stopping criterion varies by algorithm; possible criteria include: a subset score exceeds a threshold, a program's maximum allowed run time has been surpassed, etc.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Alternative search-based techniques are based on targeted projection pursuit which finds low-dimensional projections of the data that score highly: the features that have the largest projections in the lower-dimensional space are then selected.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] These scores are computed between a candidate feature (or set of features) and the desired output category.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] There are, however, true metrics that are a simple function of the mutual information; see here.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The choice of optimality criteria is difficult as there are multiple objectives in a feature selection task.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Many common criteria incorporate a measure of accuracy, penalised by the number of features selected.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Examples include Akaike information criterion (AIC) and Mallows's *Cp*, which have a penalty of 2 for each added feature.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] AIC is based on information theory, and is effectively derived via the maximum entropy principle.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] A maximum entropy rate criterion may also be used to select the most relevant subset of features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Filter feature selection is a specific case of a more general paradigm called structure learning.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Feature selection finds the relevant feature set for a specific target variable whereas structure learning finds the relationships between all the variables, usually by expressing these relationships as a graph.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The most common structure learning algorithms assume the data is generated by a Bayesian Network, and so the structure is a directed graphical model.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The optimal solution to the filter feature selection problem is the Markov blanket of the target node, and in a Bayesian Network, there is a unique Markov Blanket for each node.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] There are different Feature Selection mechanisms around that utilize mutual information for scoring the different features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The simplest approach uses the mutual information as the "derived" score.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] However, there are different approaches, that try to reduce the redundancy between features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Peng *et al.* proposed a feature selection method that can use either mutual information, correlation, or distance/similarity scores to select features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The aim is to penalise a feature's relevancy by its redundancy in the presence of the other selected features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Suppose that there are n full-set features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Let *xi* be the set membership indicator function for feature *fi*, so that *xi*=1 indicates presence and *xi*=0 indicates absence of the feature *fi* in the globally optimal feature set.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The mRMR algorithm is an approximation of the theoretically optimal maximum-dependency feature selection algorithm that maximizes the mutual information between the joint distribution of the selected features and the classification variable.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] As mRMR approximates the combinatorial estimation problem with a series of much smaller problems, each of which only involves two variables, it thus uses pairwise joint probabilities which are more robust.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] In certain situations the algorithm may underestimate the usefulness of features as it has no way to measure interactions between features which can increase relevancy.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] This can lead to poor performance when the features are individually useless, but are useful when combined (a pathological case is found when the class is a parity function of the features).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Overall the algorithm is more efficient (in terms of the amount of data required) than the theoretically optimal max-dependency selection, yet produces a feature set with little pairwise redundancy.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] mRMR is an instance of a large class of filter methods which trade off between relevancy and redundancy in different ways.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] mRMR is a typical example of an incremental greedy strategy for feature selection: once a feature has been selected, it cannot be deselected at a later stage.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] where $F_{n\times 1}=[I(f_{1};c),\ldots ,I(f_{n};c)]^{T}$ is the vector of feature relevancy assuming there are n features in total, $H_{n\times n}=[I(f_{i};f_{j})]_{i,j=1\ldots n}$ is the matrix of feature pairwise redundancy, and $\mathbf {x} _{n\times 1}$ represents relative feature weights.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] QPFS is solved via quadratic programming.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] It is recently shown that QFPS is biased towards features with smaller entropy, due to its placement of the feature self redundancy term $I(f_{i};f_{i})$ on the diagonal of H.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] An advantage of SPECCMI is that it can be solved simply via finding the dominant eigenvector of Q, thus is very scalable.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] SPECCMI also handles second-order feature interaction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] In a study of different scores Brown et al. recommended the joint mutual information as a good score for feature selection.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The score tries to find the feature, that adds the most new information to the already selected features, in order to avoid redundancy.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The score uses the conditional mutual information and the mutual information to estimate the redundancy between the already selected features ( $f_{j}\in S$ ) and the feature under investigation ( $f_{i}$ ).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] For high-dimensional and small sample data (e.g., dimensionality > 105 and the number of samples < 103), the Hilbert-Schmidt Independence Criterion Lasso (HSIC Lasso) is useful.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] HSIC always takes a non-negative value, and is zero if and only if two random variables are statistically independent when a universal reproducing kernel such as the Gaussian kernel is used.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] where $\|\cdot \|_{F}$ is the Frobenius norm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The optimization problem is a Lasso problem, and thus it can be efficiently solved with a state-of-the-art Lasso solver such as the dual augmented Lagrangian method.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The correlation feature selection (CFS) measure evaluates subsets of features on the basis of the following hypothesis: "Good feature subsets contain features highly correlated with the classification, yet uncorrelated to each other".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Here, ${\overline {r_{cf}}}$ is the average value of all feature-classification correlations, and ${\overline {r_{ff}}}$ is the average value of all feature-feature correlations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The $r_{cf_{i}}$ and $r_{f_{i}f_{j}}$ variables are referred to as correlations, but are not necessarily Pearson's correlation coefficient or Spearman's ρ.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Hall's dissertation uses neither of these, but uses three different measures of relatedness, minimum description length (MDL), symmetrical uncertainty, and relief.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The combinatorial problems above are, in fact, mixed 0–1 linear programming problems that can be solved by using branch-and-bound algorithms.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The features from a decision tree or a tree ensemble are shown to be redundant.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] A recent method called regularized tree can be used for feature subset selection.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Regularized trees penalize using a variable similar to the variables selected at previous tree nodes for splitting the current node.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Regularized trees only need build one tree model (or one tree ensemble model) and thus are computationally efficient.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Regularized trees naturally handle numerical and categorical features, interactions and nonlinearities.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] They are invariant to attribute scales (units) and insensitive to outliers, and thus, require little data preprocessing such as normalization.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Regularized random forest (RRF) is one type of regularized trees.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The guided RRF is an enhanced RRF which is guided by the importance scores from an ordinary random forest.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] A metaheuristic is a general description of an algorithm dedicated to solve difficult (typically NP-hard problem) optimization problems for which there is no classical solving methods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Generally, a metaheuristic is a stochastic algorithm tending to reach a global optimum.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] There are many metaheuristics, from a simple local search to a complex global search algorithm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The feature selection methods are typically presented in three classes based on how they combine the selection algorithm and the model building.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Filter type methods select variables regardless of the model.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] They are based only on general features like the correlation with the variable to predict.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Filter methods suppress the least interesting variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] The other variables will be part of a classification or a regression model used to classify or to predict data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] These methods are particularly effective in computation time and robust to overfitting.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Filter methods tend to select redundant variables when they do not consider the relationships between variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] However, more elaborate features try to minimize this problem by removing variables highly correlated to each other, such as the Fast Correlation Based Filter (FCBF) algorithm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Wrapper methods evaluate subsets of variables which allows, unlike filter approaches, to detect the possible interactions amongst variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Embedded methods have been recently proposed that try to combine the advantages of both previous methods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] A learning algorithm takes advantage of its own variable selection process and performs feature selection and classification simultaneously, such as the FRMT algorithm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] This is a survey of the application of feature selection metaheuristics lately used in the literature.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/feature-selection] Some learning algorithms perform feature selection as part of their overall operation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] High dimensional data can be hard for machines to work with, requiring significant time and space for analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It also presents a challenge for humans, since it's hard to visualize or understand data in more than three dimensions.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Reducing the dimensionality of a data set, while keeping its essential features relatively intact, can make algorithms more efficient and allow analysts to visualize trends and patterns.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The reduced-dimensional representations of data are often referred to as "intrinsic variables".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] This description implies that these are the values from which the data was produced.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] For example, consider a dataset that contains images of a letter 'A', which has been scaled and rotated by varying amounts.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Each image can be represented as a vector of 1024 pixel values.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Each row is a sample on a two-dimensional manifold in 1024-dimensional space (a Hamming space).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The intrinsic dimensionality is two, because two variables (rotation and scale) were varied in order to produce the data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Information about the shape or look of a letter 'A' is not part of the intrinsic variables because it is the same in every instance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Nonlinear dimensionality reduction will discard the correlated information (the letter 'A') and recover only the varying information (rotation and scale).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] By comparison, if principal component analysis, which is a linear dimensionality reduction algorithm, is used to reduce this same dataset into two dimensions, the resulting values are not so well organized.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] This demonstrates that the high-dimensional vectors (each representing a letter 'A') that sample this manifold vary in a non-linear manner.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It should be apparent, therefore, that NLDR has several applications in the field of computer-vision.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] For example, consider a robot that uses a camera to navigate in a closed static environment.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The images obtained by that camera can be considered to be samples on a manifold in high-dimensional space, and the intrinsic variables of that manifold will represent the robot's position and orientation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Invariant manifolds are of general interest for model order reduction in dynamical systems.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In particular, if there is an attracting invariant manifold in the phase space, nearby trajectories will converge onto it and stay on it indefinitely, rendering it a candidate for dimensionality reduction of the dynamical system.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] While such manifolds are not guaranteed to exist in general, the theory of spectral submanifolds (SSM) gives conditions for the existence of unique attracting invariant objects in a broad class of dynamical systems.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Active research in NLDR seeks to unfold the observation manifolds associated with dynamical systems to develop modeling techniques.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Some of the more prominent **nonlinear dimensionality reduction** techniques are listed below.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Sammon's mapping is one of the first and most popular NLDR techniques.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The self-organizing map (SOM, also called *Kohonen map*) and its probabilistic variant generative topographic mapping (GTM) use a point representation in the embedded space to form a latent variable model based on a non-linear mapping from the embedded space to the high-dimensional space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] These techniques are related to work on density networks, which also are based around the same probabilistic model.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Perhaps the most widely used algorithm for dimensional reduction is kernel PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It then projects the data onto the first *k* eigenvectors of that matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It then projects the transformed data onto the first *k* eigenvectors of that matrix, just like PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It uses the kernel trick to factor away much of the computation, such that the entire process can be performed without actually computing $\Phi (\mathbf {x} )$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Of course $\Phi$ must be chosen such that it has a known corresponding kernel.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, it is not trivial to find a good kernel for a given problem, so KPCA does not yield good results with some problems when using standard kernels.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] For example, it is known to perform poorly with these kernels on the Swiss roll manifold.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] However, one can view certain other methods that perform well in such settings (e.g., Laplacian Eigenmaps, LLE) as special cases of kernel PCA by constructing a data-dependent kernel matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] KPCA has an internal model, so it can be used to map points onto its embedding that were not available at training time.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Laplacian eigenmaps uses spectral techniques to perform dimensionality reduction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] This technique relies on the basic assumption that the data lies in a low-dimensional manifold in a high-dimensional space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] This algorithm cannot embed out-of-sample points, but techniques based on Reproducing kernel Hilbert space regularization exist for adding this capability.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Such techniques can be applied to other nonlinear dimensionality reduction algorithms as well.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Traditional techniques like principal component analysis do not consider the intrinsic geometry of the data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Laplacian eigenmaps builds a graph from neighborhood information of the data set.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Each data point serves as a node on the graph and connectivity between nodes is governed by the proximity of neighboring points (using e.g. the k-nearest neighbor algorithm).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The graph thus generated can be considered as a discrete approximation of the low-dimensional manifold in the high-dimensional space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Minimization of a cost function based on the graph ensures that points close to each other on the manifold are mapped close to each other in the low-dimensional space, preserving local distances.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The eigenfunctions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator on the manifold serve as the embedding dimensions, since under mild conditions this operator has a countable spectrum that is a basis for square integrable functions on the manifold (compare to Fourier series on the unit circle manifold).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Attempts to place Laplacian eigenmaps on solid theoretical ground have met with some success, as under certain nonrestrictive assumptions, the graph Laplacian matrix has been shown to converge to the Laplace–Beltrami operator as the number of points goes to infinity.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Isomap is a combination of the Floyd–Warshall algorithm with classic Multidimensional Scaling (MDS).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Classic MDS takes a matrix of pair-wise distances between all points and computes a position for each point.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Isomap assumes that the pair-wise distances are only known between neighboring points, and uses the Floyd–Warshall algorithm to compute the pair-wise distances between all other points.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] This effectively estimates the full matrix of pair-wise geodesic distances between all of the points.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Isomap then uses classic MDS to compute the reduced-dimensional positions of all the points.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Landmark-Isomap is a variant of this algorithm that uses landmarks to increase speed, at the cost of some accuracy.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In manifold learning, the input data is assumed to be sampled from a low dimensional manifold that is embedded inside of a higher-dimensional vector space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The main intuition behind MVU is to exploit the local linearity of manifolds and create a mapping that preserves local neighbourhoods at every point of the underlying manifold.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Locally-linear Embedding (LLE) was presented at approximately the same time as Isomap.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It has several advantages over Isomap, including faster optimization when implemented to take advantage of sparse matrix algorithms, and better results with many problems.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] LLE also begins by finding a set of the nearest neighbors of each point.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It then computes a set of weights for each point that best describes the point as a linear combination of its neighbors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Finally, it uses an eigenvector-based optimization technique to find the low-dimensional embedding of points, such that each point is still described with the same linear combination of its neighbors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] LLE tends to handle non-uniform sample densities poorly because there is no fixed unit to prevent the weights from drifting as various regions differ in sample densities.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The original data points $X_{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{D}$ , and the goal of LLE is to embed each point $X_{i}$ to some low-dimensional point $Y_{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where $d\ll D$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In the **first** step, it computes, for each point *X**i*, the best approximation of *X**i* based on barycentric coordinates of its neighbors *X**j*.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The original point is approximately reconstructed by a linear combination, given by the weight matrix *W**ij*, of its neighbors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The weights *W**ij* refer to the amount of contribution the point *X**j* has while reconstructing the point *X**i*.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] These two constraints ensure that W is unaffected by rotation and translation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In the **second** step, a neighborhood preserving map is created based the weights.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Unlike in the previous cost function, the weights Wij are kept fixed and the minimization is done on the points Yi to optimize the coordinates.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] This minimization problem can be solved by solving a sparse *N* X *N* eigenvalue problem (*N* being the number of data points), whose bottom *d* nonzero eigen vectors provide an orthogonal set of coordinates.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The only hyperparameter in the algorithm is what counts as a "neighbor" of a point.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Generally the data points are reconstructed from *K* nearest neighbors, as measured by Euclidean distance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In this case, the algorithm has only one integer-valued hyperparameter *K,* which can be chosen by cross validation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Like LLE, Hessian LLE is also based on sparse matrix techniques.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It tends to yield results of a much higher quality than LLE.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, it has a very costly computational complexity, so it is not well-suited for heavily sampled manifolds.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Modified LLE (MLLE) is another LLE variant which uses multiple weights in each neighborhood to address the local weight matrix conditioning problem which leads to distortions in LLE maps.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Loosely speaking the multiple weights are the local orthogonal projection of the original weights produced by LLE.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The theoretical and empirical implications from the correct application of this algorithm are far-reaching.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] LTSA is based on the intuition that when a manifold is correctly unfolded, all of the tangent hyperplanes to the manifold will become aligned.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It begins by computing the *k*-nearest neighbors of every point.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It computes the tangent space at every point by computing the *d*-first principal components in each local neighborhood.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It then optimizes to find an embedding that aligns the tangent spaces.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Maximum Variance Unfolding, Isomap and Locally Linear Embedding share a common intuition relying on the notion that if a manifold is properly unfolded, then variance over the points is maximized.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Its initial step, like Isomap and Locally Linear Embedding, is finding the *k*-nearest neighbors of every point.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It then seeks to solve the problem of maximizing the distance between all non-neighboring points, constrained such that the distances between neighboring points are preserved.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The primary contribution of this algorithm is a technique for casting this problem as a semidefinite programming problem.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, semidefinite programming solvers have a high computational cost.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Like Locally Linear Embedding, it has no internal model.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] An autoencoder is a feed-forward neural network which is trained to approximate the identity function.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] That is, it is trained to map from a vector of values to the same vector.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] When used for dimensionality reduction purposes, one of the hidden layers in the network is limited to contain only a small number of network units.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Thus, the network must learn to encode the vector into a small number of dimensions and then decode it back into the original space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Thus, the first half of the network is a model which maps from high to low-dimensional space, and the second half maps from low to high-dimensional space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Although the idea of autoencoders is quite old, training of deep autoencoders has only recently become possible through the use of restricted Boltzmann machines and stacked denoising autoencoders.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Related to autoencoders is the NeuroScale algorithm, which uses stress functions inspired by multidimensional scaling and Sammon mappings (see above) to learn a non-linear mapping from the high-dimensional to the embedded space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The mappings in NeuroScale are based on radial basis function networks.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Gaussian process latent variable models (GPLVM) are probabilistic dimensionality reduction methods that use Gaussian Processes (GPs) to find a lower dimensional non-linear embedding of high dimensional data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] They are an extension of the Probabilistic formulation of PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The model is defined probabilistically and the latent variables are then marginalized and parameters are obtained by maximizing the likelihood.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Like kernel PCA they use a kernel function to form a non linear mapping (in the form of a Gaussian process).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] However, in the GPLVM the mapping is from the embedded(latent) space to the data space (like density networks and GTM) whereas in kernel PCA it is in the opposite direction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It was originally proposed for visualization of high dimensional data but has been extended to construct a shared manifold model between two observation spaces.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] GPLVM and its many variants have been proposed specially for human motion modeling, e.g., back constrained GPLVM, GP dynamic model (GPDM), balanced GPDM (B-GPDM) and topologically constrained GPDM.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] To capture the coupling effect of the pose and gait manifolds in the gait analysis, a multi-layer joint gait-pose manifolds was proposed.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Relational perspective map is a multidimensional scaling algorithm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The algorithm finds a configuration of data points on a manifold by simulating a multi-particle dynamic system on a closed manifold, where data points are mapped to particles and distances (or dissimilarity) between data points represent a repulsive force.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] As the manifold gradually grows in size the multi-particle system cools down gradually and converges to a configuration that reflects the distance information of the data points.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Relational perspective map was inspired by a physical model in which positively charged particles move freely on the surface of a ball.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Guided by the Coulomb force between particles, the minimal energy configuration of the particles will reflect the strength of repulsive forces between the particles.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The Relational perspective map was introduced in.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The algorithm firstly used the flat torus as the image manifold, then it has been extended (in the software VisuMap to use other types of closed manifolds, like the sphere, projective space, and Klein bottle, as image manifolds.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Contagion maps use multiple contagions on a network to map the nodes as a point cloud.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In the case of the Global cascades model the speed of the spread can be adjusted with the threshold parameter $t\in [0,1]$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] For $t=0$ the contagion map is equivalent to the Isomap algorithm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Curvilinear component analysis (CCA) looks for the configuration of points in the output space that preserves original distances as much as possible while focusing on small distances in the output space (conversely to Sammon's mapping which focus on small distances in original space).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It should be noticed that CCA, as an iterative learning algorithm, actually starts with focus on large distances (like the Sammon algorithm), then gradually change focus to small distances.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The small distance information will overwrite the large distance information, if compromises between the two have to be made.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The stress function of CCA is related to a sum of right Bregman divergences.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] CDA trains a self-organizing neural network to fit the manifold and seeks to preserve geodesic distances in its embedding.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It is based on Curvilinear Component Analysis (which extended Sammon's mapping), but uses geodesic distances instead.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Diffeomorphic Dimensionality Reduction or *Diffeomap* learns a smooth diffeomorphic mapping which transports the data onto a lower-dimensional linear subspace.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The methods solves for a smooth time indexed vector field such that flows along the field which start at the data points will end at a lower-dimensional linear subspace, thereby attempting to preserve pairwise differences under both the forward and inverse mapping.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Manifold alignment takes advantage of the assumption that disparate data sets produced by similar generating processes will share a similar underlying manifold representation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] By learning projections from each original space to the shared manifold, correspondences are recovered and knowledge from one domain can be transferred to another.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Most manifold alignment techniques consider only two data sets, but the concept extends to arbitrarily many initial data sets.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Diffusion maps leverages the relationship between heat diffusion and a random walk (Markov Chain); an analogy is drawn between the diffusion operator on a manifold and a Markov transition matrix operating on functions defined on the graph whose nodes were sampled from the manifold.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In particular, let a data set be represented by $\mathbf {X} =[x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}]\in \Omega \subset \mathbf {R^{D}}$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The underlying assumption of diffusion map is that the high-dimensional data lies on a low-dimensional manifold of dimension $\mathbf {d}$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Let **X** represent the data set and $\mu$ represent the distribution of the data points on **X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Further, define a **kernel** which represents some notion of affinity of the points in **X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Thus one can think of the individual data points as the nodes of a graph and the kernel *k* as defining some sort of affinity on that graph.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The graph is symmetric by construction since the kernel is symmetric.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It is easy to see here that from the tuple (**X**,**k**) one can construct a reversible Markov Chain.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] This technique is common to a variety of fields and is known as the graph Laplacian.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] For example, the graph **K** = (*X*,*E*) can be constructed using a Gaussian kernel.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] In the above equation, $x_{i}\sim x_{j}$ denotes that $x_{i}$ is a nearest neighbor of $x_{j}$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Properly, Geodesic distance should be used to actually measure distances on the manifold.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Since the exact structure of the manifold is not available, for the nearest neighbors the geodesic distance is approximated by euclidean distance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The former means that very little diffusion has taken place while the latter implies that the diffusion process is nearly complete.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Different strategies to choose $\sigma$ can be found in.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] P now represents a Markov chain. $P(x_{i},x_{j})$ is the probability of transitioning from $x_{i}$ to $x_{j}$ in one time step.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Similarly the probability of transitioning from $x_{i}$ to $x_{j}$ in **t** time steps is given by $P^{t}(x_{i},x_{j})$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Here $P^{t}$ is the matrix P multiplied by itself **t** times.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The Markov matrix P constitutes some notion of local geometry of the data set **X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The major difference between diffusion maps and principal component analysis is that only local features of the data are considered in diffusion maps as opposed to taking correlations of the entire data set.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] K defines a random walk on the data set which means that the kernel captures some local geometry of data set.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The Markov chain defines fast and slow directions of propagation through the kernel values.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] As the walk propagates forward in time, the local geometry information aggregates in the same way as local transitions (defined by differential equations) of the dynamical system.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] For fixed t, $D_{t}$ defines a distance between any two points of the data set based on path connectivity: the value of $D_{t}(x,y)$ will be smaller the more paths that connect **x** to **y** and vice versa.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Local Multidimensional Scaling performs multidimensional scaling in local regions, and then uses convex optimization to fit all the pieces together.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Nonlinear PCA (NLPCA) uses backpropagation to train a multi-layer perceptron (MLP) to fit to a manifold.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Unlike typical MLP training, which only updates the weights, NLPCA updates both the weights and the inputs.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] That is, both the weights and inputs are treated as latent values.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] After training, the latent inputs are a low-dimensional representation of the observed vectors, and the MLP maps from that low-dimensional representation to the high-dimensional observation space.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Manifold Sculpting uses graduated optimization to find an embedding.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Like other algorithms, it computes the *k*-nearest neighbors and tries to seek an embedding that preserves relationships in local neighborhoods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It slowly scales variance out of higher dimensions, while simultaneously adjusting points in lower dimensions to preserve those relationships.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] If the rate of scaling is small, it can find very precise embeddings.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It boasts higher empirical accuracy than other algorithms with several problems.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It can also be used to refine the results from other manifold learning algorithms.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It struggles to unfold some manifolds, however, unless a very slow scaling rate is used.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] RankVisu is designed to preserve rank of neighborhood rather than distance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] RankVisu is especially useful on difficult tasks (when the preservation of distance cannot be achieved satisfyingly).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Indeed, the rank of neighborhood is less informative than distance (ranks can be deduced from distances but distances cannot be deduced from ranks) and its preservation is thus easier.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Topologically constrained isometric embedding (TCIE) is an algorithm based on approximating geodesic distances after filtering geodesics inconsistent with the Euclidean metric.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] Aimed at correcting the distortions caused when Isomap is used to map intrinsically non-convex data, TCIE uses weight least-squares MDS in order to obtain a more accurate mapping.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The TCIE algorithm first detects possible boundary points in the data, and during computation of the geodesic length marks inconsistent geodesics, to be given a small weight in the weighted stress majorization that follows.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE) is widely used.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It is one of a family of stochastic neighbor embedding methods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The algorithm computes the probability that pairs of datapoints in the high-dimensional space are related, and then chooses low-dimensional embeddings which produce a similar distribution.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] It works in a similar fashion as the t-SNE, with the main difference being the inclusion of a repulsive term to move far points away from each other.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] A method based on proximity matrices is one where the data is presented to the algorithm in the form of a similarity matrix or a distance matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] These methods all fall under the broader class of metric multidimensional scaling.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/manifold-learning] The variations tend to be differences in how the proximity data is computed; for example, isomap, locally linear embeddings, maximum variance unfolding, and Sammon mapping (which is not in fact a mapping) are examples of metric multidimensional scaling methods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The data are linearly transformed onto a new coordinate system such that the directions (principal components) capturing the largest variation in the data can be easily identified.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The **principal components** of a collection of points in a real coordinate space are a sequence of p unit vectors, where the i -th vector is the direction of a line that best fits the data while being orthogonal to the first $i-1$ vectors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Here, a best-fitting line is defined as one that minimizes the average squared perpendicular distance from the points to the line.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] These directions (i.e., principal components) constitute an orthonormal basis in which different individual dimensions of the data are linearly uncorrelated.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Many studies use the first two principal components in order to plot the data in two dimensions and to visually identify clusters of closely related data points.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Principal component analysis has applications in many fields such as population genetics, microbiome studies, and atmospheric science.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] When performing PCA, the first principal component of a set of p variables is the derived variable formed as a linear combination of the original variables that explains the most variance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The second principal component explains the most variance in what is left once the effect of the first component is removed, and we may proceed through p iterations until all the variance is explained.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is most commonly used when many of the variables are highly correlated with each other and it is desirable to reduce their number to an independent set.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The first principal component can equivalently be defined as a direction that maximizes the variance of the projected data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The i -th principal component can be taken as a direction orthogonal to the first $i-1$ principal components that maximizes the variance of the projected data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] For either objective, it can be shown that the principal components are eigenvectors of the data's covariance matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Thus, the principal components are often computed by eigendecomposition of the data covariance matrix or singular value decomposition of the data matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is the simplest of the true eigenvector-based multivariate analyses and is closely related to factor analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Factor analysis typically incorporates more domain-specific assumptions about the underlying structure and solves eigenvectors of a slightly different matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is also related to canonical correlation analysis (CCA).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] CCA defines coordinate systems that optimally describe the cross-covariance between two datasets while PCA defines a new orthogonal coordinate system that optimally describes variance in a single dataset.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Robust and L1-norm-based variants of standard PCA have also been proposed.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA was invented in 1901 by Karl Pearson, as an analogue of the principal axis theorem in mechanics; it was later independently developed and named by Harold Hotelling in the 1930s.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA can be thought of as fitting a *p*-dimensional ellipsoid to the data, where each axis of the ellipsoid represents a principal component.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] If some axis of the ellipsoid is small, then the variance along that axis is also small.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] To find the axes of the ellipsoid, we must first center the values of each variable in the dataset on 0 by subtracting the mean of the variable's observed values from each of those values.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] These transformed values are used instead of the original observed values for each of the variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Then, we compute the covariance matrix of the data and calculate the eigenvalues and corresponding eigenvectors of this covariance matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Then we must normalize each of the orthogonal eigenvectors to turn them into unit vectors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Once this is done, each of the mutually-orthogonal unit eigenvectors can be interpreted as an axis of the ellipsoid fitted to the data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This choice of basis will transform the covariance matrix into a diagonalized form, in which the diagonal elements represent the variance of each axis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The proportion of the variance that each eigenvector represents can be calculated by dividing the eigenvalue corresponding to that eigenvector by the sum of all eigenvalues.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Biplots and scree plots (degree of explained variance) are used to interpret findings of the PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] in such a way that the individual variables $t_{1},\dots ,t_{l}$ of **t** considered over the data set successively inherit the maximum possible variance from **X**, with each coefficient vector **w** constrained to be a unit vector.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The quantity to be maximised can be recognised as a Rayleigh quotient.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] A standard result for a positive semidefinite matrix such as **X**T**X** is that the quotient's maximum possible value is the largest eigenvalue of the matrix, which occurs when ***w*** is the corresponding eigenvector.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] With **w**(1) found, the first principal component of a data vector **x**(*i*) can then be given as a score *t*1(*i*) = **x**(*i*) ⋅ **w**(1) in the transformed co-ordinates, or as the corresponding vector in the original variables, {**x**(*i*) ⋅ **w**(1)} **w**(1).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] It turns out that this gives the remaining eigenvectors of **X**T**X**, with the maximum values for the quantity in brackets given by their corresponding eigenvalues.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Thus the weight vectors are eigenvectors of **X**T**X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **W** is a *p*-by-*p* matrix of weights whose columns are the eigenvectors of **X**T**X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The transpose of **W** is sometimes called the whitening or sphering transformation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Columns of **W** multiplied by the square root of corresponding eigenvalues, that is, eigenvectors scaled up by the variances, are called *loadings* in PCA or in Factor analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] where the eigenvalue property of **w**(*k*) has been used to move from line 2 to line 3.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] However eigenvectors **w**(*j*) and **w**(*k*) corresponding to eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are orthogonal (if the eigenvalues are different), or can be orthogonalised (if the vectors happen to share an equal repeated value).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The product in the final line is therefore zero; there is no sample covariance between different principal components over the dataset.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Another way to characterise the principal components transformation is therefore as the transformation to coordinates which diagonalise the empirical sample covariance matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **Λ** is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues *λ*(*k*) of **X**T**X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The transformation **P** = **X** **W** maps a data vector **x**(*i*) from an original space of *x* variables to a new space of *p* variables which are uncorrelated over the dataset.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] These norms are used to transform the original space of variables *x, y* to a new space of uncorrelated variables *p, q* (given *Yc* with same meaning), such that $p_{i}={\frac {X_{i}}{X_{c}}},\quad q_{i}={\frac {Y_{i}}{Y_{c}}}$ ; and the new variables are linearly related as: $q=\alpha p$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Such dimensionality reduction can be a very useful step for visualising and processing high-dimensional datasets, while still retaining as much of the variance in the dataset as possible.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Similarly, in regression analysis, the larger the number of explanatory variables allowed, the greater is the chance of overfitting the model, producing conclusions that fail to generalise to other datasets.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] One approach, especially when there are strong correlations between different possible explanatory variables, is to reduce them to a few principal components and then run the regression against them, a method called principal component regression.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Dimensionality reduction may also be appropriate when the variables in a dataset are noisy.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, with more of the total variance concentrated in the first few principal components compared to the same noise variance, the proportionate effect of the noise is less—the first few components achieve a higher signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA thus can have the effect of concentrating much of the signal into the first few principal components, which can usefully be captured by dimensionality reduction; while the later principal components may be dominated by noise, and so disposed of without great loss.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] If the dataset is not too large, the significance of the principal components can be tested using parametric bootstrap, as an aid in determining how many principal components to retain.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] where **$\mathbf {\hat {\Sigma }}$** is the square diagonal matrix with the singular values of **X**and the excess zeros chopped off that satisfies**$\mathbf {{\hat {\Sigma }}^{2}} =\mathbf {\Sigma } ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {\Sigma }$**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Comparison with the eigenvector factorization of **X**T**X** establishes that the right singular vectors **W** of **X** are equivalent to the eigenvectors of **X**T**X**, while the singular values *σ*(*k*) of **$\mathbf {X}$** are equal to the square-root of the eigenvalues *λ*(*k*) of **X**T**X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] so each column of **T** is given by one of the left singular vectors of **X** multiplied by the corresponding singular value.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This form is also the polar decomposition of **T**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Efficient algorithms exist to calculate the SVD of **X** without having to form the matrix **X**T**X**, so computing the SVD is now the standard way to calculate a principal components analysis from a data matrix, unless only a handful of components are required.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The singular values (in **Σ**) are the square roots of the eigenvalues of the matrix **X**T**X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Each eigenvalue is proportional to the portion of the "variance" (more correctly of the sum of the squared distances of the points from their multidimensional mean) that is associated with each eigenvector.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The sum of all the eigenvalues is equal to the sum of the squared distances of the points from their multidimensional mean.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA essentially rotates the set of points around their mean in order to align with the principal components.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This moves as much of the variance as possible (using an orthogonal transformation) into the first few dimensions.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The values in the remaining dimensions, therefore, tend to be small and may be dropped with minimal loss of information (see below).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is often used in this manner for dimensionality reduction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA has the distinction of being the optimal orthogonal transformation for keeping the subspace that has largest "variance" (as defined above).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This advantage, however, comes at the price of greater computational requirements if compared, for example, and when applicable, to the discrete cosine transform, and in particular to the DCT-II which is simply known as the "DCT".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques tend to be more computationally demanding than PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is sensitive to the scaling of the variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Mathematically this sensitivity comes from the way a rescaling changes the sample‑covariance matrix that PCA diagonalises.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Because the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of $\Sigma ^{(\alpha )}$ are those of $\Sigma$ scaled by D , the principal axes rotate toward any column whose variance has been inflated, exactly as the 2‑D example below illustrates.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] If we have just two variables and they have the same sample variance and are completely correlated, then the PCA will entail a rotation by 45° and the "weights" (they are the cosines of rotation) for the two variables with respect to the principal component will be equal.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] But if we multiply all values of the first variable by 100, then the first principal component will be almost the same as that variable, with a small contribution from the other variable, whereas the second component will be almost aligned with the second original variable.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This means that whenever the different variables have different units (like temperature and mass), PCA is a somewhat arbitrary method of analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] (Different results would be obtained if one used Fahrenheit rather than Celsius for example.) Pearson's original paper was entitled "On Lines and Planes of Closest Fit to Systems of Points in Space" – "in space" implies physical Euclidean space where such concerns do not arise.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] One way of making the PCA less arbitrary is to use variables scaled so as to have unit variance, by standardizing the data and hence use the autocorrelation matrix instead of the autocovariance matrix as a basis for PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, this compresses (or expands) the fluctuations in all dimensions of the signal space to unit variance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Classical PCA assumes the cloud of points has already been translated so its centroid is at the origin.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] where $\mathbf {Z}$ is the centered matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The rank‑one term $n\,{\boldsymbol {\mu }}{\boldsymbol {\mu }}^{\mathsf {T}}$ often dominates, forcing the leading eigenvector to point almost exactly toward the mean and obliterating any structure in the centred part $\mathbf {Z}$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] After mean subtraction that term vanishes and the principal axes align with the true directions of maximal variance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Mean-centering is unnecessary if performing a principal components analysis on a correlation matrix, as the data are already centered after calculating correlations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Correlations are derived from the cross-product of two standard scores (Z-scores) or statistical moments (hence the name: *Pearson Product-Moment Correlation*).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Also see the article by Kromrey & Foster-Johnson (1998) on *"Mean-centering in Moderated Regression: Much Ado About Nothing"*.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Since covariances are correlations of normalized variables (Z- or standard-scores) a PCA based on the correlation matrix of **X** is equal to a PCA based on the covariance matrix of **Z**, the standardized version of **X**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is a popular primary technique in pattern recognition.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] It is not, however, optimized for class separability.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] However, it has been used to quantify the distance between two or more classes by calculating center of mass for each class in principal component space and reporting Euclidean distance between center of mass of two or more classes.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The linear discriminant analysis is an alternative which is optimized for class separability.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The statistical implication of this property is that the last few PCs are not simply unstructured left-overs after removing the important PCs.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Because these last PCs have variances as small as possible they are useful in their own right.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] They can help to detect unsuspected near-constant linear relationships between the elements of x, and they may also be useful in regression, in selecting a subset of variables from x, and in outlier detection.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] As noted above, the results of PCA depend on the scaling of the variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This can be cured by scaling each feature by its standard deviation, so that one ends up with dimensionless features with unital variance.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The applicability of PCA as described above is limited by certain (tacit) assumptions made in its derivation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In particular, PCA can capture linear correlations between the features but fails when this assumption is violated (see Figure 6a in the reference).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In some cases, coordinate transformations can restore the linearity assumption and PCA can then be applied (see kernel PCA).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Another limitation is the mean-removal process before constructing the covariance matrix for PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In fields such as astronomy, all the signals are non-negative, and the mean-removal process will force the mean of some astrophysical exposures to be zero, which consequently creates unphysical negative fluxes, and forward modeling has to be performed to recover the true magnitude of the signals.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] As an alternative method, non-negative matrix factorization focusing only on the non-negative elements in the matrices is well-suited for astrophysical observations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] See more at the relation between PCA and non-negative matrix factorization.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA is at a disadvantage if the data has not been standardized before applying the algorithm to it.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA transforms the original data into data that is relevant to the principal components of that data, which means that the new data variables cannot be interpreted in the same ways that the originals were.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] They are linear interpretations of the original variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Also, if PCA is not performed properly, there is a high likelihood of information loss.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] If a dataset has a pattern hidden inside it that is nonlinear, then PCA can actually steer the analysis in the complete opposite direction of progress.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Researchers at Kansas State University discovered that the sampling error in their experiments impacted the bias of PCA results.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] "If the number of subjects or blocks is smaller than 30, and/or the researcher is interested in PC's beyond the first, it may be better to first correct for the serial correlation, before PCA is conducted".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The researchers at Kansas State also found that PCA could be "seriously biased if the autocorrelation structure of the data are not correctly handled".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Dimensionality reduction results in a loss of information, in general.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] PCA-based dimensionality reduction tends to minimize that information loss, under certain signal and noise models.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] that is, that the data vector $\mathbf {x}$ is the sum of the desired information-bearing signal $\mathbf {s}$ and a noise signal $\mathbf {n}$ one can show that PCA can be optimal for dimensionality reduction, from an information-theoretic point-of-view.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The optimality of PCA is also preserved if the noise $\mathbf {n}$ is iid and at least more Gaussian (in terms of the Kullback–Leibler divergence) than the information-bearing signal $\mathbf {s}$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In general, even if the above signal model holds, PCA loses its information-theoretic optimality as soon as the noise $\mathbf {n}$ becomes dependent.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The following is a detailed description of PCA using the covariance method as opposed to the correlation method.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The goal is to transform a given data set **X** of dimension *p* to an alternative data set **Y** of smaller dimension *L*.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] **Calculate the deviations from the mean** Mean subtraction is an integral part of the solution towards finding a principal component basis that minimizes the mean square error of approximating the data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Hence we proceed by centering the data as follows: In some applications, each variable (column of **B**) may also be scaled to have a variance equal to 1 (see Z-score).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This step affects the calculated principal components, but makes them independent of the units used to measure the different variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] **Project the data onto the new basis** That is, the first column of $\mathbf {T}$ is the projection of the data points onto the first principal component, the second column is the projection onto the second principal component, etc.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Let **X** be a *d*-dimensional random vector expressed as column vector.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Without loss of generality, assume **X** has zero mean.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] We want to find $(\ast )$ a *d* × *d* orthonormal transformation matrix **P** so that **PX** has a diagonal covariance matrix (that is, **PX** is a random vector with all its distinct components pairwise uncorrelated).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Hence $(\ast )$ holds if and only if $\operatorname {cov} (X)$ were diagonalisable by P .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This is very constructive, as cov(**X**) is guaranteed to be a non-negative definite matrix and thus is guaranteed to be diagonalisable by some unitary matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In practical implementations, especially with high dimensional data (large p), the naive covariance method is rarely used because it is not efficient due to high computational and memory costs of explicitly determining the covariance matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The covariance-free approach avoids the *np*2 operations of explicitly calculating and storing the covariance matrix **XTX**, instead utilizing one of matrix-free methods, for example, based on the function evaluating the product **XT(X r)** at the cost of 2*np* operations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] One way to compute the first principal component efficiently is shown in the following pseudo-code, for a data matrix **X** with zero mean, without ever computing its covariance matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This power iteration algorithm simply calculates the vector **XT(X r)**, normalizes, and places the result back in **r**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The eigenvalue is approximated by **rT (XTX) r**, which is the Rayleigh quotient on the unit vector **r** for the covariance matrix **XTX**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] If the largest singular value is well separated from the next largest one, the vector **r** gets close to the first principal component of **X** within the number of iterations c, which is small relative to p, at the total cost *2cnp*.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The power iteration convergence can be accelerated without noticeably sacrificing the small cost per iteration using more advanced matrix-free methods, such as the Lanczos algorithm or the Locally Optimal Block Preconditioned Conjugate Gradient (LOBPCG) method.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Subsequent principal components can be computed one-by-one via deflation or simultaneously as a block.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In the former approach, imprecisions in already computed approximate principal components additively affect the accuracy of the subsequently computed principal components, thus increasing the error with every new computation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The latter approach in the block power method replaces single-vectors **r** and **s** with block-vectors, matrices **R** and **S**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Every column of **R** approximates one of the leading principal components, while all columns are iterated simultaneously.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The main calculation is evaluation of the product **XT(X R)**.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Implemented, for example, in LOBPCG, efficient blocking eliminates the accumulation of the errors, allows using high-level BLAS matrix-matrix product functions, and typically leads to faster convergence, compared to the single-vector one-by-one technique.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The matrix deflation by subtraction is performed by subtracting the outer product, **t**1**r**1T from **X** leaving the deflated residual matrix used to calculate the subsequent leading PCs.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] For large data matrices, or matrices that have a high degree of column collinearity, NIPALS suffers from loss of orthogonality of PCs due to machine precision round-off errors accumulated in each iteration and matrix deflation by subtraction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] A Gram–Schmidt re-orthogonalization algorithm is applied to both the scores and the loadings at each iteration step to eliminate this loss of orthogonality.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In an "online" or "streaming" situation with data arriving piece by piece rather than being stored in a single batch, it is useful to make an estimate of the PCA projection that can be updated sequentially.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] This can be done efficiently, but requires different algorithms.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] In exploratory data analysis, qualitative (categorical) variables not used to construct the model can be projected onto the principal component axes as supplementary elements.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] The use of supplementary qualitative variables was a defining feature of the French school of data analysis developed in the 1960s and 70s.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p01] Based upon the work of Ludovic Lebart, the method is available in the R environment through packages such as FactoMineR.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The earliest application of factor analysis was in locating and measuring components of human intelligence.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The pioneering statistical psychologist Spearman actually developed factor analysis in 1904 for his two-factor theory of intelligence, adding a formal technique to the science of psychometrics.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1924 Thurstone looked for 56 factors of intelligence, developing the notion of Mental Age.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Standard IQ tests today are based on this early work.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1949, Shevky and Williams introduced the theory of **factorial ecology**, which dominated studies of residential differentiation from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Neighbourhoods in a city were recognizable or could be distinguished from one another by various characteristics which could be reduced to three by factor analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] These were known as 'social rank' (an index of occupational status), 'familism' or family size, and 'ethnicity'; Cluster analysis could then be applied to divide the city into clusters or precincts according to values of the three key factor variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] An extensive literature developed around factorial ecology in urban geography, but the approach went out of fashion after 1980 as being methodologically primitive and having little place in postmodern geographical paradigms.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] One of the problems with factor analysis has always been finding convincing names for the various artificial factors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 2000, Flood revived the factorial ecology approach to show that principal components analysis actually gave meaningful answers directly, without resorting to factor rotation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The principal components were actually dual variables or shadow prices of 'forces' pushing people together or apart in cities.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first component was 'accessibility', the classic trade-off between demand for travel and demand for space, around which classical urban economics is based.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The next two components were 'disadvantage', which keeps people of similar status in separate neighbourhoods (mediated by planning), and ethnicity, where people of similar ethnic backgrounds try to co-locate.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] About the same time, the Australian Bureau of Statistics defined distinct indexes of advantage and disadvantage taking the first principal component of sets of key variables that were thought to be important.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] These SEIFA indexes are regularly published for various jurisdictions, and are used frequently in spatial analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA can be used as a formal method for the development of indexes.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] As an alternative confirmatory composite analysis has been proposed to develop and assess indexes.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The City Development Index was developed by PCA from about 200 indicators of city outcomes in a 1996 survey of 254 global cities.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first principal component was subject to iterative regression, adding the original variables singly until about 90% of its variation was accounted for.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The index ultimately used about 15 indicators but was a good predictor of many more variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Its comparative value agreed very well with a subjective assessment of the condition of each city.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The coefficients on items of infrastructure were roughly proportional to the average costs of providing the underlying services, suggesting the Index was actually a measure of effective physical and social investment in the city.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The country-level Human Development Index (HDI) from UNDP, which has been published since 1990 and is very extensively used in development studies, has very similar coefficients on similar indicators, strongly suggesting it was originally constructed using PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In 1978 Cavalli-Sforza and others pioneered the use of principal components analysis (PCA) to summarise data on variation in human gene frequencies across regions.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The components showed distinctive patterns, including gradients and sinusoidal waves.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] They interpreted these patterns as resulting from specific ancient migration events.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Since then, PCA has been ubiquitous in population genetics, with thousands of papers using PCA as a display mechanism.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Genetics varies largely according to proximity, so the first two principal components actually show spatial distribution and may be used to map the relative geographical location of different population groups, thereby showing individuals who have wandered from their original locations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA in genetics has been technically controversial, in that the technique has been performed on discrete non-normal variables and often on binary allele markers.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The lack of any measures of standard error in PCA are also an impediment to more consistent usage.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In August 2022, the molecular biologist Eran Elhaik published a theoretical paper in Scientific Reports analyzing 12 PCA applications.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] He concluded that it was easy to manipulate the method, which, in his view, generated results that were 'erroneous, contradictory, and absurd.' Specifically, he argued, the results achieved in population genetics were characterized by cherry-picking and circular reasoning.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Market research has been an extensive user of PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is used to develop customer satisfaction or customer loyalty scores for products, and with clustering, to develop market segments that may be targeted with advertising campaigns, in much the same way as factorial ecology will locate geographical areas with similar characteristics.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA rapidly transforms large amounts of data into smaller, easier-to-digest variables that can be more rapidly and readily analyzed.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In any consumer questionnaire, there are series of questions designed to elicit consumer attitudes, and principal components seek out latent variables underlying these attitudes.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, the Oxford Internet Survey in 2013 asked 2000 people about their attitudes and beliefs, and from these analysts extracted four principal component dimensions, which they identified as 'escape', 'social networking', 'efficiency', and 'problem creating'.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Another example from Joe Flood in 2008 extracted an attitudinal index toward housing from 28 attitude questions in a national survey of 2697 households in Australia.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The first principal component represented a general attitude toward property and home ownership.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The index, or the attitude questions it embodied, could be fed into a General Linear Model of tenure choice.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The strongest determinant of private renting by far was the attitude index, rather than income, marital status or household type.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In quantitative finance, PCA is used in financial risk management, and has been applied to other problems such as portfolio optimization.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is commonly used in problems involving fixed income securities and portfolios, and interest rate derivatives.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Valuations here depend on the entire yield curve, comprising numerous highly correlated instruments, and PCA is used to define a set of components or factors that explain rate movements, thereby facilitating the modelling.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] One common risk management application is to calculating value at risk, VaR, applying PCA to the Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Here, for each simulation-sample, the components are stressed, and rates, and in turn option values, are then reconstructed; with VaR calculated, finally, over the entire run.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is also used in hedging exposure to interest rate risk, given partial durations and other sensitivities.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Under both, the first three, typically, principal components of the system are of interest (representing "shift", "twist", and "curvature").
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] These principal components are derived from an eigen-decomposition of the covariance matrix of yield at predefined maturities; and where the variance of each component is its eigenvalue (and as the components are orthogonal, no correlation need be incorporated in subsequent modelling).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] For equity, an optimal portfolio is one where the expected return is maximized for a given level of risk, or alternatively, where risk is minimized for a given return; see Markowitz model for discussion.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Thus, one approach is to reduce portfolio risk, where allocation strategies are applied to the "principal portfolios" instead of the underlying stocks.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] A second approach is to enhance portfolio return, using the principal components to select companies' stocks with upside potential.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA has also been used to understand relationships between international equity markets, and within markets between groups of companies in industries or sectors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA may also be applied to stress testing, essentially an analysis of a bank's ability to endure a hypothetical adverse economic scenario.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] A variant of principal components analysis is used in neuroscience to identify the specific properties of a stimulus that increases a neuron's probability of generating an action potential.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] This technique is known as spike-triggered covariance analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In a typical application an experimenter presents a white noise process as a stimulus (usually either as a sensory input to a test subject, or as a current injected directly into the neuron) and records a train of action potentials, or spikes, produced by the neuron as a result.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Presumably, certain features of the stimulus make the neuron more likely to spike.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In order to extract these features, the experimenter calculates the covariance matrix of the *spike-triggered ensemble*, the set of all stimuli (defined and discretized over a finite time window, typically on the order of 100 ms) that immediately preceded a spike.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Specifically, the eigenvectors with the largest positive eigenvalues correspond to the directions along which the variance of the spike-triggered ensemble showed the largest positive change compared to the variance of the prior.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Since these were the directions in which varying the stimulus led to a spike, they are often good approximations of the sought after relevant stimulus features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In neuroscience, PCA is also used to discern the identity of a neuron from the shape of its action potential.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Spike sorting is an important procedure because extracellular recording techniques often pick up signals from more than one neuron.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In spike sorting, one first uses PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the space of action potential waveforms, and then performs clustering analysis to associate specific action potentials with individual neurons.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA as a dimension reduction technique is particularly suited to detect coordinated activities of large neuronal ensembles.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] It has been used in determining collective variables, that is, order parameters, during phase transitions in the brain.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Correspondence analysis (CA) was developed by Jean-Paul Benzécri and is conceptually similar to PCA, but scales the data (which should be non-negative) so that rows and columns are treated equivalently.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is traditionally applied to contingency tables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] CA decomposes the chi-squared statistic associated to this table into orthogonal factors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Because CA is a descriptive technique, it can be applied to tables for which the chi-squared statistic is appropriate or not.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Several variants of CA are available including detrended correspondence analysis and canonical correspondence analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] One special extension is multiple correspondence analysis, which may be seen as the counterpart of principal component analysis for categorical data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Principal component analysis creates variables that are linear combinations of the original variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The new variables have the property that the variables are all orthogonal.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The PCA transformation can be helpful as a pre-processing step before clustering.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is a variance-focused approach seeking to reproduce the total variable variance, in which components reflect both common and unique variance of the variable.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] PCA is generally preferred for purposes of data reduction (that is, translating variable space into optimal factor space) but not when the goal is to detect the latent construct or factors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Factor analysis is similar to principal component analysis, in that factor analysis also involves linear combinations of variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Different from PCA, factor analysis is a correlation-focused approach seeking to reproduce the inter-correlations among variables, in which the factors "represent the common variance of variables, excluding unique variance".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In terms of the correlation matrix, this corresponds with focusing on explaining the off-diagonal terms (that is, shared co-variance), while PCA focuses on explaining the terms that sit on the diagonal.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, as a side result, when trying to reproduce the on-diagonal terms, PCA also tends to fit relatively well the off-diagonal correlations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Results given by PCA and factor analysis are very similar in most situations, but this is not always the case, and there are some problems where the results are significantly different.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Factor analysis is generally used when the research purpose is detecting data structure (that is, latent constructs or factors) or causal modeling.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] If the factor model is incorrectly formulated or the assumptions are not met, then factor analysis will give erroneous results.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] It has been asserted that the relaxed solution of *k*-means clustering, specified by the cluster indicators, is given by the principal components, and the PCA subspace spanned by the principal directions is identical to the cluster centroid subspace.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, that PCA is a useful relaxation of *k*-means clustering was not a new result, and it is straightforward to uncover counterexamples to the statement that the cluster centroid subspace is spanned by the principal directions.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Non-negative matrix factorization (NMF) is a dimension reduction method where only non-negative elements in the matrices are used, which is therefore a promising method in astronomy, in the sense that astrophysical signals are non-negative.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The PCA components are orthogonal to each other, while the NMF components are all non-negative and therefore constructs a non-orthogonal basis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In PCA, the contribution of each component is ranked based on the magnitude of its corresponding eigenvalue, which is equivalent to the fractional residual variance (FRV) in analyzing empirical data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] For NMF, its components are ranked based only on the empirical FRV curves.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The FRV curves for NMF is decreasing continuously when the NMF components are constructed sequentially, indicating the continuous capturing of quasi-static noise; then converge to higher levels than PCA, indicating the less over-fitting property of NMF.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is often difficult to interpret the principal components when the data include many variables of various origins, or when some variables are qualitative.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] This leads the PCA user to a delicate elimination of several variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] If observations or variables have an excessive impact on the direction of the axes, they should be removed and then projected as supplementary elements.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In addition, it is necessary to avoid interpreting the proximities between the points close to the center of the factorial plane.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The iconography of correlations, on the contrary, which is not a projection on a system of axes, does not have these drawbacks.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] We can therefore keep all the variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The principle of the diagram is to underline the "remarkable" correlations of the correlation matrix, by a solid line (positive correlation) or dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] A strong correlation is not "remarkable" if it is not direct, but caused by the effect of a third variable.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Conversely, weak correlations can be "remarkable".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, if a variable Y depends on several independent variables, the correlations of Y with each of them are weak and yet "remarkable".
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] A particular disadvantage of PCA is that the principal components are usually linear combinations of all input variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Sparse PCA overcomes this disadvantage by finding linear combinations that contain just a few input variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] It extends the classic method of principal component analysis (PCA) for the reduction of dimensionality of data by adding sparsity constraint on the input variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The methodological and theoretical developments of Sparse PCA as well as its applications in scientific studies were recently reviewed in a survey paper.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Most of the modern methods for nonlinear dimensionality reduction find their theoretical and algorithmic roots in PCA or K-means.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Pearson's original idea was to take a straight line (or plane) which will be "the best fit" to a set of data points.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Trevor Hastie expanded on this concept by proposing **Principal curves** as the natural extension for the geometric interpretation of PCA, which explicitly constructs a manifold for data approximation followed by projecting the points onto it.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] See also the elastic map algorithm and principal geodesic analysis.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Another popular generalization is kernel PCA, which corresponds to PCA performed in a reproducing kernel Hilbert space associated with a positive definite kernel.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] In multilinear subspace learning, PCA is generalized to multilinear PCA (MPCA) that extracts features directly from tensor representations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA is solved by performing PCA in each mode of the tensor iteratively.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA has been applied to face recognition, gait recognition, etc.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] MPCA is further extended to uncorrelated MPCA, non-negative MPCA and robust MPCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] While PCA finds the mathematically optimal method (as in minimizing the squared error), it is still sensitive to outliers in the data that produce large errors, something that the method tries to avoid in the first place.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] It is therefore common practice to remove outliers before computing PCA.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] However, in some contexts, outliers can be difficult to identify.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] For example, in data mining algorithms like correlation clustering, the assignment of points to clusters and outliers is not known beforehand.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] A recently proposed generalization of PCA based on a weighted PCA increases robustness by assigning different weights to data objects based on their estimated relevancy.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Outlier-resistant variants of PCA have also been proposed, based on L1-norm formulations (L1-PCA).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Robust principal component analysis (RPCA) via decomposition in low-rank and sparse matrices is a modification of PCA that works well with respect to grossly corrupted observations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Independent component analysis (ICA) is directed to similar problems as principal component analysis, but finds additively separable components rather than successive approximations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Given a matrix E , it tries to decompose it into two matrices such that $E=AP$ .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] A key difference from techniques such as PCA and ICA is that some of the entries of A are constrained to be 0.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Each column of A must have at least $L-1$ zeroes where L is the number of columns of A (or alternatively the number of rows of P ).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The justification for this criterion is that if a node is removed from the regulatory layer along with all the output nodes connected to it, the result must still be characterized by a connectivity matrix with full column rank.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] then the decomposition is unique up to multiplication by a scalar.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Discriminant analysis of principal components (DAPC) is a multivariate method used to identify and describe clusters of genetically related individuals.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Genetic variation is partitioned into two components: variation between groups and within groups, and it maximizes the former.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Linear discriminants are linear combinations of alleles which best separate the clusters.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Alleles that most contribute to this discrimination are therefore those that are the most markedly different across groups.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] A DAPC can be realized on R using the package Adegenet.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Directional component analysis (DCA) is a method used in the atmospheric sciences for analysing multivariate datasets.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Like PCA, it allows for dimension reduction, improved visualization and improved interpretability of large data-sets.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Also like PCA, it is based on a covariance matrix derived from the input dataset.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The difference between PCA and DCA is that DCA additionally requires the input of a vector direction, referred to as the impact.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] Whereas PCA maximises explained variance, DCA maximises probability density given impact.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] The motivation for DCA is to find components of a multivariate dataset that are both likely (measured using probability density) and important (measured using the impact).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/principal-component-analysis-p02] DCA has been used to find the most likely and most serious heat-wave patterns in weather prediction ensembles , and the most likely and most impactful changes in rainfall due to climate change .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In machine learning (ML), **feature learning** or **representation learning** is a set of techniques that allow a system to automatically discover the representations needed for feature detection or classification from raw data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] This replaces manual feature engineering and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that ML tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] However, real-world data, such as image, video, and sensor data, have not yielded to attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Supervised feature learning is learning features from labeled data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The data label allows the system to compute an error term, the degree to which the system fails to produce the label, which can then be used as feedback to correct the learning process (reduce/minimize the error).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Dictionary learning develops a set (dictionary) of representative elements from the input data such that each data point can be represented as a weighted sum of the representative elements.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The dictionary elements and the weights may be found by minimizing the average representation error (over the input data), together with *L1* regularization on the weights to enable sparsity (i.e., the representation of each data point has only a few nonzero weights).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Supervised dictionary learning exploits both the structure underlying the input data and the labels for optimizing the dictionary elements.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] For example, this supervised dictionary learning technique applies dictionary learning on classification problems by jointly optimizing the dictionary elements, weights for representing data points, and parameters of the classifier based on the input data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Neural networks are a family of learning algorithms that use a "network" consisting of multiple layers of inter-connected nodes.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] It is inspired by the animal nervous system, where the nodes are viewed as neurons and edges are viewed as synapses.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Each edge has an associated weight, and the network defines computational rules for passing input data from the network's input layer to the output layer.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] A network function associated with a neural network characterizes the relationship between input and output layers, which is parameterized by the weights.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] With appropriately defined network functions, various learning tasks can be performed by minimizing a cost function over the network function (weights).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Multilayer neural networks can be used to perform feature learning, since they learn a representation of their input at the hidden layer(s) which is subsequently used for classification or regression at the output layer.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The most popular network architecture of this type is Siamese networks.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Unsupervised feature learning is learning features from unlabeled data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The goal of unsupervised feature learning is often to discover low-dimensional features that capture some structure underlying the high-dimensional input data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] When the feature learning is performed in an unsupervised way, it enables a form of semisupervised learning where features learned from an unlabeled dataset are then employed to improve performance in a supervised setting with labeled data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Several approaches are introduced in the following.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] K-means clustering can be used to group an unlabeled set of inputs into *k* clusters, and then use the centroids of these clusters to produce features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] These features can be produced in several ways.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The simplest is to add *k* binary features to each sample, where each feature *j* has value one iff the *j*th centroid learned by *k*-means is the closest to the sample under consideration.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] It is also possible to use the distances to the clusters as features, perhaps after transforming them through a radial basis function (a technique that has been used to train RBF networks).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Coates and Ng note that certain variants of *k*-means behave similarly to sparse coding algorithms.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In a comparative evaluation of unsupervised feature learning methods, Coates, Lee and Ng found that *k*-means clustering with an appropriate transformation outperforms the more recently invented auto-encoders and RBMs on an image classification task.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] *K*-means also improves performance in the domain of NLP, specifically for named-entity recognition; there, it competes with Brown clustering, as well as with distributed word representations (also known as neural word embeddings).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Principal component analysis (PCA) is often used for dimension reduction.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Equivalently, these singular vectors are the eigenvectors corresponding to the *p* largest eigenvalues of the sample covariance matrix of the input vectors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] These *p* singular vectors are the feature vectors learned from the input data, and they represent directions along which the data has the largest variations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] PCA is a linear feature learning approach since the *p* singular vectors are linear functions of the data matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The singular vectors can be generated via a simple algorithm with *p* iterations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In the *i*th iteration, the projection of the data matrix on the *(i-1)*th eigenvector is subtracted, and the *i*th singular vector is found as the right singular vector corresponding to the largest singular of the residual data matrix.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] First, it assumes that the directions with large variance are of most interest, which may not be the case.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] PCA only relies on orthogonal transformations of the original data, and it exploits only the first- and second-order moments of the data, which may not well characterize the data distribution.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Furthermore, PCA can effectively reduce dimension only when the input data vectors are correlated (which results in a few dominant eigenvalues).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Local linear embedding (LLE) is a nonlinear learning approach for generating low-dimensional neighbor-preserving representations from (unlabeled) high-dimension input.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The approach was proposed by Roweis and Saul (2000).
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The general idea of LLE is to reconstruct the original high-dimensional data using lower-dimensional points while maintaining some geometric properties of the neighborhoods in the original data set.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The second step is for "dimension reduction," by looking for vectors in a lower-dimensional space that minimizes the representation error using the optimized weights in the first step.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Note that in the first step, the weights are optimized with fixed data, which can be solved as a least squares problem.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In the second step, lower-dimensional points are optimized with fixed weights, which can be solved via sparse eigenvalue decomposition.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The reconstruction weights obtained in the first step capture the "intrinsic geometric properties" of a neighborhood in the input data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] It is assumed that original data lie on a smooth lower-dimensional manifold, and the "intrinsic geometric properties" captured by the weights of the original data are also expected to be on the manifold.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] This is why the same weights are used in the second step of LLE.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Compared with PCA, LLE is more powerful in exploiting the underlying data structure.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Independent component analysis (ICA) is a technique for forming a data representation using a weighted sum of independent non-Gaussian components.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The assumption of non-Gaussian is imposed since the weights cannot be uniquely determined when all the components follow Gaussian distribution.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Unsupervised dictionary learning does not utilize data labels and exploits the structure underlying the data for optimizing dictionary elements.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] An example of unsupervised dictionary learning is sparse coding, which aims to learn basis functions (dictionary elements) for data representation from unlabeled input data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Sparse coding can be applied to learn overcomplete dictionaries, where the number of dictionary elements is larger than the dimension of the input data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Aharon et al. proposed algorithm K-SVD for learning a dictionary of elements that enables sparse representation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The hierarchical architecture of the biological neural system inspires deep learning architectures for feature learning by stacking multiple layers of learning nodes.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] These architectures are often designed based on the assumption of distributed representation: observed data is generated by the interactions of many different factors on multiple levels.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In a deep learning architecture, the output of each intermediate layer can be viewed as a representation of the original input data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Each level uses the representation produced by the previous, lower level as input, and produces new representations as output, which are then fed to higher levels.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The input at the bottom layer is raw data, and the output of the final, highest layer is the final low-dimensional feature or representation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Restricted Boltzmann machines (RBMs) are often used as a building block for multilayer learning architectures.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] An RBM can be represented by an undirected bipartite graph consisting of a group of binary hidden variables, a group of visible variables, and edges connecting the hidden and visible nodes.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] It is a special case of the more general Boltzmann machines with the constraint of no intra-node connections.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Each edge in an RBM is associated with a weight.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The weights together with the connections define an energy function, based on which a joint distribution of visible and hidden nodes can be devised.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Based on the topology of the RBM, the hidden (visible) variables are independent, conditioned on the visible (hidden) variables.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Such conditional independence facilitates computations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] An RBM can be viewed as a single layer architecture for unsupervised feature learning.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In particular, the visible variables correspond to input data, and the hidden variables correspond to feature detectors.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The weights can be trained by maximizing the probability of visible variables using Hinton's contrastive divergence (CD) algorithm.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In general, training RBMs by solving the maximization problem tends to result in non-sparse representations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Sparse RBM was proposed to enable sparse representations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The idea is to add a regularization term in the objective function of data likelihood, which penalizes the deviation of the expected hidden variables from a small constant p .
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] RBMs have also been used to obtain *disentangled* representations of data, where interesting features map to separate hidden units.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] An autoencoder consisting of an encoder and a decoder is a paradigm for deep learning architectures.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] An example is provided by Hinton and Salakhutdinov where the encoder uses raw data (e.g., image) as input and produces feature or representation as output and the decoder uses the extracted feature from the encoder as input and reconstructs the original input raw data as output.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The encoder and decoder are constructed by stacking multiple layers of RBMs.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The parameters involved in the architecture were originally trained in a greedy layer-by-layer manner: after one layer of feature detectors is learned, they are fed up as visible variables for training the corresponding RBM.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Current approaches typically apply end-to-end training with stochastic gradient descent methods.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Training can be repeated until some stopping criteria are satisfied.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation learning is learning features by training on the structure of unlabeled data rather than relying on explicit labels for an information signal.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] This approach has enabled the combined use of deep neural network architectures and larger unlabeled datasets to produce deep feature representations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Training tasks typically fall under the classes of either contrastive, generative or both.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Contrastive representation learning trains representations for associated data pairs, called positive samples, to be aligned, while pairs with no relation, called negative samples, are contrasted.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] A larger portion of negative samples is typically necessary in order to prevent catastrophic collapse, which is when all inputs are mapped to the same representation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Generative representation learning tasks the model with producing the correct data to either match a restricted input or reconstruct the full input from a lower dimensional representation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] A common setup for self-supervised representation learning of a certain data type (e.g. text, image, audio, video) is to pretrain the model using large datasets of general context, unlabeled data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Depending on the context, the result of this is either a set of representations for common data segments (e.g. words) which new data can be broken into, or a neural network able to convert each new data point (e.g. image) into a set of lower dimensional features.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] In either case, the output representations can then be used as an initialization in many different problem settings where labeled data may be limited.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Specialization of the model to specific tasks is typically done with supervised learning, either by fine-tuning the model / representations with the labels as the signal, or freezing the representations and training an additional model which takes them as an input.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Many self-supervised training schemes have been developed for use in representation learning of various modalities, often first showing successful application in text or image before being transferred to other data types.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Word2vec is a word embedding technique which learns to represent words through self-supervision over each word and its neighboring words in a sliding window across a large corpus of text.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The model has two possible training schemes to produce word vector representations, one generative and one contrastive.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The first is word prediction given each of the neighboring words as an input.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The second is training on the representation similarity for neighboring words and representation dissimilarity for random pairs of words.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] A limitation of word2vec is that only the pairwise co-occurrence structure of the data is used, and not the ordering or entire set of context words.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] More recent transformer-based representation learning approaches attempt to solve this with word prediction tasks.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] GPTs pretrain on next word prediction using prior input words as context, whereas BERT masks random tokens in order to provide bidirectional context.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Other self-supervised techniques extend word embeddings by finding representations for larger text structures such as sentences or paragraphs in the input data.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Doc2vec extends the generative training approach in word2vec by adding an additional input to the word prediction task based on the paragraph it is within, and is therefore intended to represent paragraph level context.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The domain of image representation learning has employed many different self-supervised training techniques, including transformation, inpainting, patch discrimination and clustering.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Many other self-supervised methods use siamese networks, which generate different views of the image through various augmentations that are then aligned to have similar representations.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] The challenge is avoiding collapsing solutions where the model encodes all images to the same representation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] SimCLR is a contrastive approach which uses negative examples in order to generate image representations with a ResNet CNN.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Bootstrap Your Own Latent (BYOL) removes the need for negative samples by encoding one of the views with a slow moving average of the model parameters as they are being modified during training.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Another approach is to maximize mutual information, a measure of similarity, between the representations of associated structures within the graph.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] An example is Deep Graph Infomax, which uses contrastive self-supervision based on mutual information between the representation of a "patch" around each node, and a summary representation of the entire graph.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Negative samples are obtained by pairing the graph representation with either representations from another graph in a multigraph training setting, or corrupted patch representations in single graph training.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] With analogous results in masked prediction and clustering, video representation learning approaches are often similar to image techniques but must utilize the temporal sequence of video frames as an additional learned structure.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Examples include VCP, which masks video clips and trains to choose the correct one given a set of clip options, and Xu et al., who train a 3D-CNN to identify the original order given a shuffled set of video clips.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Self-supervised representation techniques have also been applied to many audio data formats, particularly for speech processing.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Wav2vec 2.0 discretizes the audio waveform into timesteps via temporal convolutions, and then trains a transformer on masked prediction of random timesteps using a contrastive loss.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] This is similar to the BERT language model, except as in many SSL approaches to video, the model chooses among a set of options rather than over the entire word vocabulary.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Self-supervised learning has also been used to develop joint representations of multiple data types.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Approaches usually rely on some natural or human-derived association between the modalities as an implicit label, for instance video clips of animals or objects with characteristic sounds, or captions written to describe images.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] CLIP produces a joint image-text representation space by training to align image and text encodings from a large dataset of image-caption pairs using a contrastive loss.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Multimodal representation models are typically unable to assume direct correspondence of representations in the different modalities, since the precise alignment can often be noisy or ambiguous.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] For example, the text "dog" could be paired with many different pictures of dogs, and correspondingly a picture of a dog could be captioned with varying degrees of specificity.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] This limitation means that downstream tasks may require an additional generative mapping network between modalities to achieve optimal performance, such as in DALLE-2 for text to image generation.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Dynamic representation learning methods generate latent embeddings for dynamic systems such as dynamic networks.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Since particular distance functions are invariant under particular linear transformations, different sets of embedding vectors can actually represent the same/similar information.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Therefore, for a dynamic system, a temporal difference in its embeddings may be explained by misalignment of embeddings due to arbitrary transformations and/or actual changes in the system.
[src:dimensionality-reduction/representation-learning] Therefore, generally speaking, temporal embeddings learned via dynamic representation learning methods should be inspected for any spurious changes and be aligned before consequent dynamic analyses.
